  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">International</h3>

  <p>The sanitary emergency due to COVID-19 continued to cause a significant economic slowdown during the
    third quarter 2020. Notwithstanding, a certain improvement has been observed in the forecasts of a number
    organizations regarding the development of world economy, such as that of the International Monetary Fund
    which now expects a 4.4% YoY contraction in global GDP for 2020, positively compared to its 4.9% YoY drop
    projected as of the end of 2Q20.</p>

  <p>Likewise, the oil barrel price, which lately has posted a downward trend given a lower demand, recovered
    part of the lost ground, going from USD$34.28 at the end of June to USD$37.12 per barrel as of the end of
    September 2020.</p>

  <p>With regards to the progress attained in the search for an effective COVID-19 vaccine, especially
    outstanding are the Russian and Chinese prototypes, whose trials on monitored groups are already been
    conducted; whereas in the United States, Oxford University together with the pharmaceutical company
    AstraZeneca assured to have obtained  "positive results" in another prototype, which in words of its
    developers “still has a long way to go". In this sense, it is expected that when a vaccine that successfully
    passes all its test phases is found, thus ensuring efficacy and safety, the World Health Organization will
    work to facilitate access and distribution of said vaccine.</p>

  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">National</h3>

  <p>In Mexico, the process of “new normal” has bolstered the economy’s performance in comparison to that
    of last quarter, as attested by the figures of Monthly Economic Activity Index - IGAE (102.2 in July vs.
    88.0 in April), or the sales reported by the National Association of Department Stores - ANTAD (2.6% YoY in
    September vs. -15.3% YoY in June), thus reporting 2 and 3 months, respectively, of sequential improvement
    since the beginning of the economic reopening in June. However, analysts expect a 9.8% YoY decrease in
    2020 GDP, in accordance with a survey conducted by Mexico Central Bank (Banxico) early in October.</p>

  <p>Moreover, in order to support economic performance, during que quarter, Banxico reduced its interest
    rate by 75 basis points to 4.25%, a level not recorded since September 2016. On the other hand, the
    recent spike in inflation may limit the room for further cuts during upcoming quarters.</p>

  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">Industry</h3>

